#237 Misc
    :date: 2025-07-02 20:55
    :shortdes: How many birds die by falling?
    :tags: Nonsense | Science

.While on a two-week road trip by myself last week, I was struck with a bizarre
question, as tends to happen when you spend that long alone:
<em>how often do birds die by falling</em>?

.Obviously, in most cases if a bird falls from a height sufficient to be dangerous,
it can simply fly away.
But it seems reasonable to imagine there could be cases where this could fail
(say, there are bizarre wind conditions,
 or its wings are covered in ice,
 or it's extremely sick and doesn't have enough energy).
At any rate, it seems implausible that the number would be <em>zero</em>;
nothing in nature is ever invulnerable to physics like that!

.For the purposes of this question:

<ul>
<li>
The bird must be capable of at least limited flight under normal circumstances. E.g., an ostrich or a juvenile unfledged bird wouldn't count.
</li>
<li>
“Death by falling” requires that an impact in a primarily vertical direction be the direct cause of the bird's death. This means things like these don't count:
<ul>
<li>Crashing into a window and then falling to the ground and dying. There was a fall, but the death wasn't caused by the fall.</li>
<li>Falling off a perch and, in midair, being shot or caught by a predator.</li>
<li><a href="https://www.foxweather.com/earth-space/loon-fallout-weather-phenomenon-birds-fall-sky-wisconsin">Loon fallout</a> (yes, this is a real thing). Loons can be forced to land in bad weather due to ice forming on their wings, and loons are like airplanes – they have to take off into the wind over a long stretch of open water to get enough lift, and to make matters worse they <a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Kq-tGVPKMTY">basically can't walk</a>, so they can get stranded away from any suitable habitat and die. But again, unless the loon tried to keep flying and lost airworthiness, and died or suffered fatal injuries on impact with the ground, the fall wasn't really the cause of death.</li>
<li>Dying while in midair for some reason, and <em>then</em> falling out of the sky. (This is, of course, not <em>death by falling</em>, but rather a <em>fall by dying</em>. A large fraction of the search results I found for this were on this possibility, so I thought I'd note it.)</li>
</ul>
</li>
</ul>

<hr>

.I couldn't find a comprehensive answer, of course.

.First off, would falling even be fatal? Several sources asserted that a fall would definitely kill a bird if it happened, while others said most birds probably don't have high enough terminal velocity to be killed. I imagine it depends a bit on the bird: a hummingbird would probably be okay, but as we'll see in a moment, a turkey can definitely be killed by a free fall. Where exactly the line is seems unclear (to be fair, one has to imagine this would be a difficult thing to study empirically).

.Then, can a bird really be so incapacitated as to be unable to at least flutter around and slow its fall? I can easily imagine, say, a high branch breaking in the middle of the night, sending a sleeping bird to the ground, but I don't know much about bird physiology: maybe it's almost guaranteed to wake up. Maybe a bird caught in a tornado could become unable to fly and get thrown into the ground, but I'm not sure that would count as falling. Claude suggested the possibility of a midflight neurological event or physical injury like a lightning strike or collision causing a bird to lose control over its flight but not killing it, which sounds surprisingly plausible (like, it obviously can't happen often, but given that there are billions of birds, it seems like it must happen occasionally).

.Worst for the answerability of my question, though, how would you know if this had happened? Even if birds were frequently, say, falling out of trees and dying, it wouldn't be often that someone would happen to be standing there watching, and if they did, they probably wouldn't go call some scientist who studies bird falls and report it!

.But then, because the world is a weird, weird place, I found that in Yellville, Arkansas, there has traditionally been a Thanksgiving event <a href="https://www.quora.com/Do-eagles-get-scared-of-heights/answer/Stefan-Pociask?ch=10&share=86c19ccd&srid=GjHU">where turkeys are thrown out of a plane</a>, and many of them die, as the limited amount of flight they're equipped for isn't enough to reliably stop them on a drop from an airplane. (In recent years, it sounds like the event is no longer promoted, but someone still sometimes unofficially drops turkeys from a plane.) Amusingly (if a discussion of something this cruel can be amusing), this basically fits the criteria in the previous paragraph: locals and tourists are standing around watching for falling turkeys and see some of them hit the ground and die from the impact. So I guess we know that the number of birds that have died by falling is at least as large as the number of turkeys who have died in the Yellville Turkey Drop.

.If anyone happens to know of any (other?) weird case reports, I'd love to hear about them!

.See also <a href="#post-211">What percentage of people have ever been on an airplane?</a>


#236 Misc
    :date: 2025-06-09 20:50
    :shortdes: Comparing text with Beyond Compare
    :tags: Tech

.Just wanted to do a quick shout-out to <a href="https://www.scootersoftware.com/">Beyond Compare</a>,
a tool I've been using for years to find differences between files and folders.
I mostly use the features to compare folders to deduplicate messes (see if they have the same filenames in them, and if the files are identical)
and to compare different versions of text (not all things you need to compare fit into version control software!).

.It's a little complicated,
and I sometimes find myself clicking randomly around the interface trying to find something,
but if you're patient, it can do pretty much anything you need
(you can even write custom regex-based rules to indicate what counts as an “important difference” and ignore changes that don't matter,
 something that has saved my butt when debugging complicated issues more times than I can count).
It also has the best name of any piece of software I've ever used!


#235 Misc
    :date: 2025-05-14 23:00
    :shortdes: Why are the Twin Cities express lanes so underutilized?
    :tags: Design | Minneapolis | Society

.I once heard someone say, quite accurately, that taking an international
flight in basic economy class is the most expensive way to feel poor. That
naturally suggests the question, what's the cheapest way to feel rich?

.Well, for my money, it's paying to use the hybrid HOV/toll lanes in the Twin
Cities metro as a single occupant during heavy traffic. This weekend, on 394
westbound from downtown Minneapolis, I noticed eastbound traffic was almost at
a standstill. So on the way back 30 minutes later, I took a slight detour to
get on at a different exit where I could hop into the reversible express lanes,
and promptly whizzed past two miles of bumper-to-bumper traffic at 65mph. It
feels like you've joined the aristocracy, for the price of…75 cents. No, that's
not a typo. (Sometimes it's even less: the busier the lanes, the higher the
price.)

.Judging by how much my ETA on Google Maps changed after I switched into the
express lanes, this maneuver saved me four minutes, and it would have been more
like seven if I hadn't had to detour to be able to get into the express lanes.
$0.75 is so cheap that, mathematically, almost everyone should be willing to
pay it: at $0.75, you can buy a minute for 15 cents, so you only have to value
your time at $9 per hour to break even. Minimum wage in Minnesota is $11.13,
rising to $15.97 in Minneapolis proper. And that's if you don't attach any
negative value to the experience of sitting in traffic! Me, I'd happily pay
$0.75 to not sit in traffic even if it saved no time at all.

.I can think of at least three reasons for the underutilization, and all of
them are interesting.

.The first is that that the DOT has evidently done a terrible job of
advertising and explaining them. I brought this question up with a discussion
group of folks from across the metro, and half of them didn't even know what
express lanes I was talking about (they must live in a part of the metro where
they seldom have reason to take the highways that have them). The other half
had various misconceptions about them: they didn't know that you could pay to
use them as a single occupant; they didn't know some of the lanes are open to
everyone outside of rush hour (I <em>regularly</em> have to move over for
people tailgating me on I-35W, when they could legally drive around me in the
wide-open lane to my left!); they thought the lanes were tolled at rush hour
and HOV-only at other times; and even more.

<div class="callout">
At one point I had some grand theory about how not knowing that you could use
some of the express lanes outside of rush hour was symptomatic of a lack of
curiosity and interest in understanding your city, and then I tried to explain
that to one of the most curious people I know and they promptly went, “Wait, I
didn't know that!” I always thought that the “OPEN TO ALL TRAFFIC” sign was
pretty clear, but after having that conversation I took a closer look on my
next trip, and there are at least four different signs that say different
things that could plausibly be interpreted as contradictory. I think it's only
clear if you start out knowing how it's supposed to work, or correctly guessing it.
</div>

.The second reason is that, for some reason, people are irrationally annoyed by
paying small fees while driving. Witness how much more reluctant people will be
to drive somewhere if they have to pay $3 to park – while they cheerfully spend
$10 in gas to make the trip and $200 at their destination. Or take London's
congestion pricing scheme: initially people hated the idea and it only barely
passed at all. Twenty years on, people love the result so much that the rules
have been tightened up multiple times, and a majority of people in a recent
poll even claimed they would support <em>completely pedestrianizing all of
central London</em>! I do wonder if people just don't quite understand how
pleasant the result is. (In fact, just knowing that you <em>can</em> escape
traffic even if you don't think the price is currently worth it is worth a lot
emotionally.)

.A third reason is surely the <a href="https://mosmu.se/#TrivialInconvenience">trivial
inconvenience</a> of filling out an online government form to order a MNPass
transponder and putting it in your car (there's no other way to pay). It only
took me about 30 minutes, which you'll make back pretty quickly even if, like
me, you don't drive at times with heavy traffic all that often, but I didn't
get around to doing it until I'd been living here for a couple of years. But
it's worth knocking this one out for your future self if you live in a place
that has express lanes like this: surely at least once while you're living
there, you'll appreciate having the option to pay more to arrive faster.

.The plus side is that I can keep paying less than a dollar to stay in
free-flowing traffic and arrive home 5 minutes earlier, while everyone else
queues up and complains about how bad traffic is. So I guess I should say,
shhhh!


#234 Misc
    :date: 2025-05-13 23:45
    :shortdes: Problems I can't believe nobody has solved, part two
    :tags: Tech

.Why, in a world that has such miraculous and varied adhesives as Superglue,
Post-It Notes, and gaffer's tape, is there still no way to create a price tag
that doesn't tear into twenty-three separate pieces and leave residue when you
try to remove it after it's been attached to an object for more than a few
months?


#233 Misc
    :date: 2025-05-13 23:30
    :shortdes: An amount equal to the surface area of a finger
    :tags: Language | Math

.A few weeks ago, someone
<a href="https://english.stackexchange.com/questions/630499/put-one-drop-in-both-eyes">asked</a>
on the English Language & Usage Stack Exchange about an instruction that had appeared
on their prescription for eyedrops: “Put one drop in both eyes.”
They argued it should instead say “Put one drop in <em>each</em> eye,”
since otherwise you could interpret it as meaning that you should somehow apply a single drop to both your eyes at once.
I concluded that they were absolutely right, but also that it was not really very confusing and mostly a funny discussion for pedantic people.

.Then today I encountered this perplexing instruction on a tube of OTC antibiotic ointment from Walgreens:

<blockquote>
Adults and children 2 years old and older:
Clean affected area.
Apply a small amount (an amount equal to the surface area of a finger) on the area 1 to 3 times daily.
</blockquote>

.An amount of ointment <em>equal to the surface area of a finger?!</em>
This is a dumpster fire of an instruction.
The more I think about it, the less sense it makes.

.First off: are we talking about surface area or volume?
I contend the <em>surface area</em> of ointment one should apply is obvious:
equal to the area you're trying to medicate with the ointment.
And we don't talk about “amounts” of surface area, anyway.
If I ask how much paint I need to paint a wall,
I'm not asking about the surface area of paint I need
(that's obvious: it's the surface area of the wall!),
I'm asking about the volume of paint in the can I need to get adequate coverage.
That's what I'd expect here, too: it says to apply “a small amount”,
so the question I naturally ask when I look at the instructions is,
how much should I squeeze out of the tube and how thickly should I lay it on?

.But if the instruction is meant to tell you how much <em>volume</em> of ointment to use,
which seems like a more useful question, it makes even less sense.
You can't compare surface area and volume, it's just not meaningful.
Imagine a recipe saying, “Add an amount of water equal to the surface area of your kitchen counter.”
Actually, that's being generous:
at least if you poured water on your kitchen counter,
water has a natural thickness that it would reach before it covered the counter and started to spill off,
while ointment could be piled up thinly or thickly on the finger and still stay there.

.Besides, even ignoring the problem of thickness,
how would you go about using the surface area of your finger to measure ointment?
Spread the ointment all over your finger, and then…you've applied it to your finger and now you can't take it off?
Unless they mean, absurdly, that you should assume the thickness is some fixed amount,
then mentally roll up the film of ointment from around your finger into a ball,
then match the amount you squeeze out to that amount.

.The best guess I can come up with is that they mean
you should squeeze some ointment out of the tube until the glob roughly covers your fingertip (not your whole finger),
and then spread that amount over the wound.
I still don't think this makes much sense,
because the correct amount to use will differ depending on the size of the wound,
and it still says nothing at all about how thick it should pile up on your fingertip,
or what constitutes covering a fingertip
(just the very tip? the tip and a small area around it? the part up to the knuckle? and it doesn't even actually say the fingertip specifically).
Also, fingers are different sizes, both on the same person and across different people.
Because of all those limitations, I don't think it actually does much if anything to illuminate how much ointment I should use,
even if I were totally confident this were actually the correct interpretation, which I'm not!
But it does at least make a small amount of logical sense.

.I'll note that coming to even this uncertain guess containing almost no useful information
took me about 15 minutes,
and the very smart friend I showed this to also had absolutely no idea what it meant,
so as far as I'm concerned the instructions failed to communicate anything useful.


#232 Article
    :date: 2025-04-14 10:15
    :title: London's Forgotten Banana Nuisance
    :author: Matt Brown
    :source: https://web.archive.org/web/20250218220617/https://londonist.substack.com/p/londons-forgotten-banana-nuisance
    :tags: History | Humor

Ever wondered if cartoons where people slip on banana peels are overstating it? People don't really get hurt by banana peels that much, do they? Well, apparently before people figured out that throwing your trash all over the street wasn't a great idea, they did. According to a newspaper report, on a single day in 1902, on just two heavily trafficked streets in London, <strong>fourteen people</strong> were injured badly enough by slipping on banana peels to need medical treatment! Oranges, apparently, are just about as bad. After reading this, I find myself fastidiously moving orange and banana peels off the sidewalk any time I notice them.


