out how sperm and eggs work.


#230 Misc
    :date: 2025-04-05 16:45
    :shortdes: Design Hall of Shame: Hilton Homewood Suites, downtown Milwaukee
    :tags: Design

.Let me set the scene: I get off the train in downtown Milwaukee, walk about 10
minutes, and come up to the hotel I've booked. This is a cool old building
&ndash; where do I go to check in to my room?

.Well, after I get up to the corner and while I'm waiting for the light, I see there's
a big ENTRANCE.

<img class="center" width="500px" loading="lazy" src="assets/images/hilton-entrance.jpeg">

.Easy! Except when I go up to the ENTRANCE and pull on the handle, both doors
are locked and I can't Enter. Oh look, there's this eensy weensy sign over to
the left that's impossible to see unless you've already walked up into the
entranceway:

<img class="center" width="600px" loading="lazy" src="assets/images/hilton-entrance-oops.jpeg">

.Ok, no Key Card yet, so we need to find the Main Entrance. Let's walk further
around the building.

<img class="center" width="700px" loading="lazy" src="assets/images/hilton-alternate-entrance.jpeg">

.Well, there's a door here, but we were told to look for the Main Entrance, so
according to the sign we need to go a little bit further left.

.Here it is, but, uh:

<img class="center" width="700px" loading="lazy" src="assets/images/hilton-main-entrance.jpeg">

.Also, I'll note that it wasn't even 4:00 pm yet; apparently the Main Entrance
closed early.

.This is so comically bad I almost can't believe the hotel isn't just trying to
have a laugh. It's the kind of design fail that can easily be avoided by having
literally one person try to find their way into the hotel, or even just
<em>thinking</em> about what a random person would do on coming up to the hotel
for the first time, but nobody ever thinks to do that.


#229 Misc
    :date: 2025-03-31 16:40
    :shortdes: Beating jet lag with Timeshifter
    :tags: Tech | Travel

.I'm pretty sensitive to circadian rhythm disruptions. After large time zone
changes, I'll sometimes continue getting tired early and having malaise for
days, and even daylight saving time throws me off. My last few RemNote offsites
have been particularly annoying, as they've all been held in the Eastern
Hemisphere where a majority of our team members live, so I cross six to twelve
time zones and am zonked out while others move only a couple and are fine the
next day.

.I was in Barcelona for the last couple weeks and used a clever app called <a
href="https://www.timeshifter.com">Timeshifter</a>, which builds a
jet-lag-reduction plan for you to follow for (usually) five days, starting two
days before your trip, with recommendations on light exposure, sleep times, and
caffeine and melatonin use. The app itself is simple and well-designed – you
just add your itinerary (dates and flight numbers) and it does everything else
for you, including sending you notifications when it's time to take some
action.

.Most of the recommendations are fairly easy to follow (e.g., shift your
sleep/wake times one hour each day for the two days prior to travel, or get
bright light in the morning or evening). Sometimes they can be seriously
annoying, though (e.g., on the way back, I had to avoid light as much as
possible until noon for our last two days, which meant I was sitting in the
completely dark kitchen of our AirBNB working on my MacBook with <a
href="https://justgetflux.com">f.lux</a> manually set to Minneapolis time). You
might have to wear sunglasses indoors occasionally (for what it's worth though,
I wore them in airports and on planes quite a few times this trip, and nobody
commented or looked at me funny; YMMV). The app says it has a “practicality
filter” which understands that, e.g., you probably can't sleep while you're at
an airport waiting to board your plane, even if that would be the ideal time,
and tweaks the instructions accordingly. I wish you could manually mark
specific pieces of advice as unfollowable in your situation and have it adjust
the schedule, but the plans do seem to be reasonably forgiving if you have to
cheat occasionally.

.Verdict? I experienced essentially zero jet lag this trip. I felt normally
tired within an hour of my destination time zone's bedtime on the first day in
both directions, and never once had any trouble sleeping. This felt
<em>bizarre</em>, though of course welcome! Despite the mild annoyance of
following the plan, I'll definitely be doing it again. (And actually, I think I
kind of appreciate having strict instructions to follow during long transits –
it adds structure to an otherwise irritatingly formless period of time.)

.I will say that preparing in advance of the trip makes me feel just slightly
worse than normal for an extra two days, which might be a slight downside. But
it's very mild – more like I can tell that something's off than that I actually
feel bad. When I've tried to shift a couple hours in advance by myself in the
past, I've felt much worse for those days; the light exposure seems to be doing
a lot to keep this feeling OK. Still, if it's ever important that you're at
100% right before leaving and how you feel after arriving is relatively
unimportant, that might be a reason not to use the app for that trip, or to
skip setting up your plan until the day you depart.

.I should also note that I used the app for a trip once last year as well and,
while it still clearly helped, it wasn't quite so miraculous. However, that was
a 12-hour shift compared to a 6-hour shift – I wouldn't expect zero jet lag on
a 12-hour shift no matter what, that's just too much! I also didn't learn about
the app until just before I left, so I was unable to do the full 2 days of
pre-adaptation, which I think is quite important to its success. I'll
definitely update this next time I do a huge shift.

.Sometimes the recommendations are so bizarre you'll be tempted not to follow
them. For instance, on my return trip west, I got up at 7am and it told me to
sleep at 11am/4am on the way from Barcelona to Amsterdam (understandable
because I'd only slept 5 hours overnight and it was still dark in Minneapolis).
Then it told me to take melatonin and sleep for five hours on the transatlantic
flight at 3pm/8am (?!), which is not only a bizarre time to sleep in either
time zone, but completely contrary to the conventional wisdom that you should
avoid sleeping until a normal destination bedtime when going west. But I
figured I'd trust the process and give it a try, and it absolutely worked, even
though I had to wake up an hour and a half in for the in-flight meal and then
go to sleep again. I think it was somehow able to work out that sleeping at
this time wouldn't disrupt my adaptation but would still prevent me from
getting tired early after landing. That's the kind of thing the scientific
understanding must include somewhere, but is way too complicated to give as
advice unless it's embedded in a particular schedule.

<div class="callout">

.Several people I've talked to about the app have thought it wouldn't work for
them because they can't sleep on airplanes. So to be clear, when I say I
“sleep” on the plane, I mean I recline my seat one notch, put on
noise-canceling headphones, wrap myself in my <a
href="https://mosmu.se/#TravelBlanket">travel blanket</a>, close my eyes, and
sit still. I'll usually doze and drift a little, but I'm lucky to get more than
an hour of uninterrupted sleep at a time, if that. If I find myself getting
really bored and unable to drift at all, I'll read on my Kindle at minimum
brightness without turning on any of the lights until I start to feel a little
sleepier, which usually takes me half an hour or so, and then go back to
“sleeping”. You certainly don't need to be able to actually sleep well on a
plane for this to work. Even if you get literally no sleep, just sitting still
in the dark not doing anything will help your body adjust.

.Several people I've talked to have also been turned off by the price
($10 per trip or $25 for unlimited trips for a year). All I can say is, if
after spending thousands of dollars on a trip, getting rid of jet lag isn't
worth $10 to you, I'm jealous of how mild your jet lag must be!

</div>


#228 Misc
    :date: 2025-03-08 13:45
    :shortdes: Design Hall of Shame: GE Cync light switches
    :tags: Design

.I use GE Cync smart lightbulbs and lamp sockets in parts of my apartment so
that I can (a) bring the lights up slowly in the morning in my bedroom, and (b)
switch on and off the 8 lamps in my living room at the same time. Overall, the
system works pretty well for something that's so hilariously complex for
controlling lights (when I connected my first devices and was prompted to
<em>update my lightbulb's firmware</em>, I knew I had entered a brave new world).

.The switches you use with them are subtly awful, though:

<img class="center" width="400px" loading="lazy" src="assets/images/bad-design-cync-switch.jpg">

.The two buttons at the bottom allow you to cycle through different color
temperatures, if your light source supports them. That mostly works fine (it's
kind of silly that it cycles through only a hard-coded set of temperatures,
given that using the phone app you can create millions of different colors, but
that isn't really the hardware's fault; the left/right selector is a perfectly
fine choice).

.Then the top. The top- and bottom-most buttons adjust the brightness. The
middle buttons are “on” and “off”. What's the problem with that? Well, first of
all, buttons are a horrendous choice for adjusting the brightness of a light
source. There are 20 gradations, so if you want to go from max brightness to
min brightness, you have to press the “down” button nineteen times, or stand
there holding it down while whistling to yourself. A dial would be much, much
better.

.But what catapults this from someone cost-cutting too aggressively to a Design
Hall of Shame nomination is that it's almost impossible to reliably press the
correct button without looking at the switch…which, uh, when you consider how
light switches are typically used, is a pretty big problem! At least 25% of the
time I either push the “on” button when I meant to push the “off” button or
vice versa, or press the “brighter” button when I meant the “on” button or the
“dimmer” button when I meant the “off” button. It's certainly possible to find
the correct button by feel, but you have to run your fingers over the entire
light switch from top to bottom first, because the middles of each button feel
almost identical. The raised centerline in the middle of the “on/off” position
seems like it would help, but it's difficult to distinguish from the lip
between the on/off and dimmer sections unless you're really paying close
attention (and who's ever paying close attention to flipping a light switch?).
The engraved arrows also seem like they would help, but they're almost
imperceptible unless you're actually moving your finger over it; when you
blindly land your finger on the switch and feel a button under it, you
generally are not moving your finger enough to notice.

.I think the ideal design here would be a raised infinite-spin
volume-knob-style control plus the color temperature buttons. You would turn
the control to change the brightness, push it in to toggle between on and off,
and also be able to nudge it up or down to explicitly select “on” or “off”.
That last interaction has several motivations:

<ul>

    <li>In the very common case of reaching around the edge of a doorway to the
    light switch when entering or exiting a room, it's much easier to flick
    your hand parallel to the wall than to push <em>back into</em> the
    wall.</li>

    <li>Everyone's already used to the “flick up/down” motion. If you do it by
    mistake on the wrong kind of switch, it just does what you mean.</li>

    <li>The reason these have separate “off” and “on” buttons, rather than just
    a single toggle, is that it's possible for the switch to control many
    lights at once and for some of them to be off and some of them to be on. So
    if you have separate buttons, you can select the new state you want for the
    whole group in a single action. It's nice to maintain this capability.</li>

</ul>

.If the nudge is too expensive to get right, though, or it proves too hard to
add enough friction to not randomly spin the dimmer by mistake, a knob with
just a push-in design would still be vastly better than the current one. You'd
just make it turn all the lights off in the partially-on state, then back on
the second time you pushed it. (I think off first is better even though this is
the opposite of the typical design for partial states like this, because if
it's late at night and you have most of the lights off or dimmed, you want to
be able to shut everything off without making the room blindingly bright.
Having the lights momentarily flicker off before they all come on, when your
finger is already on the switch, is much less annoying. Another option would be
to have a timeout of a quarter second or so before the lights changed state,
during which you could double-tap to select the other action immediately.)

.Even if they didn't add a dial, a <em>tiny</em> bit more attention to tactile
feedback could have made the current design a great deal better. Just a simple
raised dot on either the on/off buttons or the dim buttons would be a huge
usability improvement. Maybe one dot on “off” and three dots on “on” (rather
like <a
href="https://www.iconfinder.com/icons/8480782/bathroom_button_dual_flush_toilet_icon">the
icons on dual-flush toilets</a>, which I've always felt are a brilliant piece
of design in that even if you've never seen a dual-flush toilet before, you can
easily figure out what the buttons do), or a circle on “off” and a sunburst on
“on”.

.Failing even that, the software could make a useful contribution by not
distinguishing between the “off” and “on” buttons if the entire group was
currently off or on already. If the entire room is dark and I push the “off”
button, it should be obvious that I intended to turn the lights on rather than
more-off.


